    {
      "title": "Savi: A Daring Thriller That Thrills No One",
      "slug": "a-thriller-that-thrills-no-one",
      "content": "<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height:0.8\">Movie Name: <strong>Savi</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height:0.8\">Cast: <strong>Anil Kapoor, Divya Khosla Kumar, Harshvardhan Rane</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height:0.8\">Director:<strong> Abhinay Deo</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height:0.8\">Genre: <strong>Thriller</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height:0.8\">Available on: <strong>Netflix</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":969,\"width\":\"166px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/11/One-Star.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-969\" style=\"width:166px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>\"Savi\" is a film that fails to entertain or move its audience, lacking the essential elements that typically draw viewers in. The movie's tagline, “A Bloody Housewife,” comes across as crude and tasteless, and whoever crafted it should reconsider their career in writing. Despite being based on the French thriller \"Anything for Her,\" this adaptation falls flat, with Divya Khosla contributing little to its success.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The film's saving grace, Anil Kapoor, delivers a commendable performance, yet his role is insufficiently substantial to satisfy the audience. Harshvardhan Rane, on the other hand, has almost no significant role, though his limited screen time spares him from further criticism.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":844,\"width\":\"632px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/Savi-2024-Movie-Ending-Explained-hof-1024x610.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-844\" style=\"width:632px;height:auto\"/></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The music, including both songs and background score, is dull and uninspiring. The protagonist's lacklustre dialogue delivery and unrealistic acting fail to evoke any emotion from the audience. It's evident that if the movie had not been produced by her husband, Bhushan Kumar’s company, Divya Khosla likely wouldn't have been cast in a leading role.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Raageshwari Loomba returns to the screen after a long hiatus, but her limited screen time and uninteresting dialogues squander her talent. One would expect gripping dialogue in a thriller, but \"Savi\" disappoints with traditional and predictable lines.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Ultimately, this movie is not recommended as it risks giving viewers a headache and making them question their judgment in selecting a so-called thriller. The bland and punchless ending further adds to the dissatisfaction, making \"Savi\" a waste of time and money for both producers and moviegoers alike.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>I give this movie one star, only because there's no option for anything lower.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->",
      "posterImage": "https://via.placeholder.com/300x450?text=Movie+Image",
      "rating": 4,
      "genre": "Drama",
      "type": "MOVIE",
      "status": "APPROVED",
      "createdAt": "2024-09-01T06:27:52.000Z"
    },
    {
      "title": "Gyaarah Gyaarah: If you want to Watch the Unoriginal and Uninspired Adaptation of an Amazing Series",
      "slug": "an-unoriginal-and-uninspired-adaptation",
      "content": "<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Series Name: <strong>Gyaarah Gyaarah</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Cast: <strong>Kritika Kamra, Raghav Juyal, Dhairya Karwa</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Director:<strong> Umesh Bist</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Genre: <strong>Sci-Fi Thriller</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Available on: <strong>Zee 5</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":776,\"width\":\"210px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-776\" style=\"width: 210px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/09/2-star.png\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The Hindi series, Gyaarah Gyaarah, directed by Umesh Bist is an adaptation of the Korean drama \"<a title=\"\" href=\"https://cinebuffs.org/2024/08/31/a-masterclass-in-sci-fi-drama/\">Signal</a>,\" and unfortunately, it falls short of expectations. Produced by notable figures like Academy Award winner Guneet Monga and Bollywood's Karan Johar, the series is set in Uttarakhand, a location eerily similar to the Korean setting in \"Signal.\" However, the similarities don't stop at the scenery. The plot, characters, and storylines are a direct rip-off of the original, leaving much to be desired in terms of originality.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Rather than adapting the story to better suit the Indian context, making it more relevant and relatable to the audience, the director opted for a scene-by-scene recreation of the Korean series. This approach not only feels uninspired but also detracts from the overall quality of the show. In several instances, even the dialogues appear to be direct translations from Korean, which only highlights the lack of creativity in the adaptation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":847,\"width\":\"677px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-847\" style=\"width: 677px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/0F8A3671-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Watching this series, I couldn't help but think that Vishal Bhardwaj is perhaps the only one who reimagines a story for an Indian audience with the authenticity and originality it deserves. He has a unique ability to transform narratives, as he did with Shakespeare’s Hamlet, adapting it into the Kashmiri tale of Haider.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>While the setting aims to be gloomy to match the tone of the series, it ends up feeling more melodramatic than truly suspenseful or intriguing. The three main characters also fail to deliver compelling performances, often making it tiring to watch them on screen. Their lacklustre acting further diminishes the potential impact of the story.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>When you have a series like \"Signal\" to compare it with, the flaws in this Hindi adaptation become even more glaring. The problem isn't just that it’s a copy, but that it’s an exact copy without any of the nuance or depth that made the original so compelling.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>As a fan of the genre, I found this series to be a significant disappointment, especially given the involvement of such prominent producers. With a second season already planned, I can't say I'm looking forward to it. This series simply doesn't live up to its potential and is not what I expected from some of the biggest names in the industry.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->",
      "posterImage": "https://via.placeholder.com/300x450?text=Movie+Image",
      "rating": 4,
      "genre": "Drama",
      "type": "MOVIE",
      "status": "APPROVED",
      "createdAt": "2024-09-02T06:40:17.000Z"
    },
    {
      "title": "Indian 2: Time Fades the Legacy of a Masterpiece",
      "slug": "time-fades-the-legacy",
      "content": "<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Movie Name: <strong>Indian 2</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Cast: <strong>Kamal Haasan, Siddharth, Priya Bhavani Shankar</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Director:<strong> Shankar</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Genre: <strong>Action Drama</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Available on: <strong>Netflix</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":740,\"width\":\"163px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-740\" style=\"width: 163px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/3-star.png\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Kamal Haasan returns to his iconic role as the aged vigilante Senapathy in this highly anticipated sequel. The film opens with a scathing portrayal of the rampant corruption and bribery plaguing India, with brutal depictions of victims' deaths intensifying the emotional impact. Directed by Shankar, Indian 2 is marked by his signature style, featuring grandiose song sequences and impressive visual effects.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The inclusion of Siddharth, Priya Bhavani Shankar, Jagan, and Rishikanth's social media channel, Barking Dogs, brings a contemporary flair to the film. Their portrayal of everyday struggles, clearly inspired by R. K. Laxman's \"The Common Man,\" adds a relatable and poignant touch, tempering the harsh realities with a dose of social commentary.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":851,\"width\":\"623px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-851\" style=\"width: 623px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/SGP3686-Copy-1024x683.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The strength of the movie lies in its compelling narrative and a surprising twist in the second half. At first glance, it appears to be yet another tale of a hero seeking to rid the country of its flaws, delivering justice to corrupt politicians and officials, often through ruthless means. However, the film cleverly explores the irony that people often reject the truth when it hits too close to home. This theme is powerfully illustrated when the very individuals who called for Senapathy's return are the ones demanding his departure by the end.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Despite some shortcomings, particularly the unrealistic makeup that seems to struggle under the scrutiny of 8K screens, Kamal Haasan's performance remains dominant and compelling in every scene. Whether the fault lies in the makeup team's execution or the high-definition display, it doesn't detract significantly from the overall experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In conclusion, this film is a worthwhile watch, with the ending hinting at a third instalment that promises to delve into the flashback of Senapathy and his father. Fans can look forward to yet another captivating offering from the Shankar-Kamal Haasan collaboration.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->",
      "posterImage": "https://via.placeholder.com/300x450?text=Movie+Image",
      "rating": 4,
      "genre": "Drama",
      "type": "MOVIE",
      "status": "APPROVED",
      "createdAt": "2024-09-03T05:57:00.000Z"
    },
    {
      "title": "Shazam! Fury of the Gods: Spectacle over Substance",
      "slug": "spectacle-over-substance",
      "content": "<!-- wp:group {\"layout\":{\"type\":\"flex\",\"orientation\":\"vertical\"}} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-group\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Movie Name: <strong>Shazam! Fury of the Gods</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Cast: <strong>Zachary Levi, Asher Angel, Jack Dylan Grazer, Helen Mirren, Lucy Liu, Rachel Zegler</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Director:<strong> David F. Sandberg</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Genre: <strong>Superhero</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"style\":{\"typography\":{\"lineHeight\":\"0.8\"}}} -->\n<p style=\"line-height: 0.8;\">Available on: <strong>Netflix</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":740,\"width\":\"174px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"full\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-full is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-740\" style=\"width: 174px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2023/08/3-star.png\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>In the sequel to the DC superhero film Shazam!, the return of the lightning-clad hero fails to live up to its predecessor. The film introduces three new antagonists—the daughters of the Titan Atlas, portrayed by Helen Mirren, Lucy Liu, and Rachel Zegler—who bring chaos into Billy Batson's world. Despite the star power and a promising premise, the movie struggles to recapture the charm and excitement of the original.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Director David F. Sandberg aims to recreate the magic of the first film but falls short due to a weak script and an unnecessarily lengthy runtime. While there are moments of humor and light-heartedness with Billy's character, the film fails to deliver the consistent laughter and fun that audiences anticipated.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"id\":857,\"width\":\"646px\",\"height\":\"auto\",\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large is-resized\"><img class=\"wp-image-857\" style=\"width: 646px; height: auto;\" src=\"https://cinebuffs.org/wp-content/uploads/2024/08/maxresdefault-3-1024x576.jpg\" alt=\"\" /></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>The film's storyline lacks the impact one would expect given its impressive cast, which may have contributed to its disappointing box office performance. The challenge of casting child actors in sequels is apparent, as their rapid growth makes it difficult for audiences to connect with their characters. This issue, combined with lackluster dialogue and an underwhelming plot, detracts from the overall experience.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Though the movie is somewhat standalone, lacking significant ties to the first film, it does set up the possibility of a third installment. The ending hints at the return of Dr. Sivana, suggesting that the next film might offer a more engaging storyline. For now, Shazam! Fury of the Gods is a watchable but forgettable entry in the superhero genre.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->",
